<rate>4< /rate>< Review>
Food is good here, location is very clean. Not a whole lot of parking, and getting to location can be a bit of a pain. Staff were great, no complaints, slight difficulty talking to cashier, but was favorite part of location. Food prepared immediately, like done in less than 3 minutes. Only had a burrito, mild salsa was good. Definitely going to come back here eventually. Didn't see if had restrooms. In all, good food at an expected price.<//Review>

<Text>I'm from Detroit, Michigan. And this place has the most authentic by far so far</Text><pictures>None<//pictures><response>None</response><gmapID>0x80dcdf9f8f72c4ef:0xa7056f656417f82b<//gmapID></record></dataset><record>
<gmapID>0x80dcdf9f8f72c4ef:0xa7056f656417f82b<//gmapID>< Review>
I don't get it. I came here because I was in the area, was wanting mexican, and the reviews were great. Did I get the off night? The food was not good and it was not a good value for what I got. I ordered a fish taco / enchilada combo and carne asada combo. I was looking forward to it too. The fish tacos are literally frozen fish sticks in a corn tortilla. I couldn't believe it. It was placed directly on the cheese enchilada in my combo which made the taco fall apart. The enchilada was just ok. The carne asada was basically burnt ground beef. Definitely not the asada I've had many many times in the past. The rice and beans was bland and under seasoned too. To top if all off there is an unannounced 4% service charge added. (I was a walk in customer...not delivery) so when I got the receipt after I paid, I saw that I paid an extra 4% on top of my gratuity bringing my total bill to nearly $40 for this meal. Sorry, that's not a good value at all...especially for what I got.< /Review>

<Text>A preferred spot for delicious Mexican food. Do yourself a favor and give this place a try. I look forward to a return visit. The bill was decent for the quality.</Text><GmapID>0x80dcdf9f8f72c4ef:0xa7056f656417f82b<//GmapID>< Response>

< userid>
116492355937056340471< /userid>
</record>
</dataset><record>
< text>
Perhaps to better describe its excellent carne deshebrada to Orange County, "Roman's Mexican Restaurant and Taqueria" has followed Chipotle in naming it "beef barbacoa," even though barbacoa in Spanish translates to barbecue and, in Mexico, barbacoa traditionally refers to pit-roasted meats.

I am 100% sure the owner of Roman's is aware that carne deshebrada, aka Mexican-style shredded beef, is not barbacoa. Carne deshebrada is culinarily closer to being the Mexican equivalent to the Caribbean-style marinated, slow-cooked beef referred to as "ropa vieja."

Roman's "Carne Deshebrada Taco" aka "Barbacoa Taco," consists of two thin white corn tortillas filled with braised beef, dressed with fresh chopped onions and cilantro. Roman's juicy carne deshebrada, due to lengthy stewing in chilies and spices, really doesn't require any additional sauce. Nonetheless, I added the salsa bar's thick salsa roja during my visit, and the smoldering combination induced delirium. This is not barbacoa, it's not even just carne deshebrada, it's heaven in a tortilla.</text>

< review>
I lived in Costa Mesa for most of my life. This place has one of the best Torta Cubanas I've had in OC. Mixed with their fresh avocado salsa verde! PERFRCTO! (It is spicy for people who cant take spice. Lol)

I also enjoy their tacos al pastor, chimichangas with shredded beef,enchiladas and their BIG chicken quesadillas! their  cheeseburgers are made very tasty as well.

It is a bit pricier but there portions are big and it is worth it!<//review>

< Review>
Amazing taqueria hidden on North Newport Blvd. in Costa Mesa! Most everything I have tried has been delicious and made to order. The carnitas are my favorite, always crispy and juicy at the same time. The tacos are huge! Definitely worth the price. The salsa bar has several varieties that are always fresh, and are comprised of all heat levels. They also have a large beverage cooler wall with many varieties of drinks, from juice, and sodas in glass bottles, to beers and teas.. Highly recommend.< /Review>

I had politely asked for whatever I wanted to drink, yet the employee taking my order was rude enough to yell at me saying that she couldn't hear what I was saying. The store wasn't that busy and it wasn't that loud for anyone to have to speak up that much. No one else did. I repeat my order and for the second time she misunderstood what I said and I had to correct her, again. She rushed taking my order and I didn't even have the chance to mention I wanted soy milk instead of the regular, until the other employee moved over to register my order on the cash register. When she rushed to make my drink, she ran around as if the ground was on fire and she basically slammed the equipment. Again, it wasn't that busy for her to run around like a machine in overdrive. I've worked at a cafe before having to serve up to 200 guests at the same time and I understand you want to help customers as quickly as possible but doing it with a bad attitude isn't going to help and it was only off-putting. I will never ever walk in to this store ever again and I will make sure anybody that I know will not as well because of a rude young man who has a title of store manager and behaves in such a disrespectful way, being a "perfect" example for other workers. You guys seriously need to re-evaluate who you hire and more importantly who you hire as managers to lead by example. Upon my observation throughout the months of visiting, he would always (10/10 times) hide behind utility room (I'm really curious what he is always doing back there during his working hours) and when I make noises from the machines he would slowly walkout as if I'm an invisible person. But as I walked out of the door strenuously carrying multiple cups of icecream as usual, he shouted at my back, "WELCOME!" thinking I'll leave without even saying thank you. I guess he thinks customers have the obligation to act certain ways but he doesn't. Moreover, he talks to everyone in such a patronizing way, its so hard to describe and extremely difficult to hear. <Review>We have lived here a little over a year and a half. I doubt any apartment is perfect, but this place is about as close as you can get. The maintenance team is always working to keep the grounds clean, fresh, and up to date.

Property management is great. They are very informative, nice, helpful, and all the ladies have a great personality. They collect your packages in case they don‚Äôt fit in your mailbox or is too sensitive to be dropped off at your door, they notify you when you have a delivery, they send out emails letting you know about apartment updates/food trucks/strong wind advisories/payment reminders (before you are late)/and general apartment information.

It‚Äôs a great place for pets. Plenty of areas for them to do their business, with proper disposal areas. And there is a park near by where you can walk your pets around.

The apartments themselves are pretty quite. We are directly above garages (we occasionally hear them open) but that is about as loud as it gets around here.  (Please understand these are apartments, you‚Äôll be living around several families....you may hear occasional chatting in the hallway, or moving in/out. However, most of our neighbors are pretty polite, and we rarely notice them.)

We have our own laundry which is incredibly convenient. The lighting is all energy efficient. We will be getting upgraded thermostats soon. The appliances are up to date (electric). The floors are light faux wood. The rooms are spacious. And you can own a BBQ. We have an elevator. (Talk about making moving day so much easier!) There is also plenty of parking. Centre Club also has pools, spas, tennis court, and a gym.

Also, the complex has food vendors who will set up in front of the office every so often. You can experience a large variety from hamburgers, hotdogs, burritos, to churros and funnel cakes, etc. It‚Äôs perfect for those nights you don‚Äôt want to cook. Head on down and buy some good food!

These apartments are in a great location as well. You will be close to groceries, shopping centers, schools, entertainment, and even an airport (which you vary rarely ever hear).

If you choose to live here. Please be a proactive member. Say hi to the staff, be kind to the ladies in the front office, pick up after your pets, and inform the staff if the complex isn‚Äôt up to par. They can‚Äôt fix it, if they don‚Äôt know it‚Äôs broken. < text>
I hoped to never need to review an emergency room, but here I am... I went to the ER with severe chest pain and pressure. Obviously a very scary experience. When I arrived I was checked in by a nurse within 5 minutes, and as soon as I was brought back to a bed I was attended to non-stop by doctors, nurses and techs. I was given multiple (necessary) tests and wasn‚Äôt discharged until they were sure what was causing my symptoms. Clearly explained everything to me to make sure I understood what was going on. They were able to relieve the symptoms and sent my results to my PCP immediately (also part of the USC system). The doctors and nurses made sure to answer all of my questions without rushing me. I never want to need the ER again, but if I do, I know I‚Äôll be in good hands at Verdugo Hills.</text>

<review>Yes and no. lol I have had great experiences here, however, I would like to also acknowledge ways in which they can be better.

PRO:

My car would stop while driving ON THE FREEWAY and it was scary. After having it towed to Roseville Honda, they took apart my car, found the problem, sent me pictures of the problem, and backed me when I approached Shell and told them they caused the problem and would like them to compensate me for the tow fees and the service provided by Honda. I felt reassured with the service team having my back.

CON:

<Name>Marty Brown<//Name>< time>
1608936300504< /time>
<Rating>4</Rating>< review>
First off, I'm a tough grader. I have enough trips around the sun to know what good customer service should look like and when employees are properly trained and motivated to provide it.

I recently reviewed this dealership because I walked onto their lot while I was having my Infiniti serviced across the street. I was impressed that the people were pleasant and not the stereotypical "What will it take to get you into this car today?" sales-types.I was kinda sorta thinking of getting a newer Honda for my wife to drive.

A couple weeks later, I was looking for a pre-owned Honda CRV and at some point questioned whether a new close-out 2020 CRV might actually be closer to my price range than I initially thought. Used car prices on some models seem to be inflated and 2020 close-out prices are pretty hot. I had a very fair price on a new CRV in Stockton and actually had an appointment to go there to buy it. But I decided to check the price at AutoNation one more time, and am very glad that I did. They came in, on the exact same model, color, and trim about $2500 less than Stockton.

Actually, this made me feel a bit uneasy. Why so cheap? What am I missing? Is this for real? AutoNation is a HUGE outfit - is this really where I want to purchase a car? Are they going to stick it to me somewhere?

I made an appointment and reserved the car and held my breath. My wife and I showed up to see the car and were both somewhat tense. We haven't purchased a new car since 2007 and were not totally comfortable with how working with a huge dealership would work. Our sales guy was pleasant, but we never really understood what the sales process was and how long it would take, not having purchased a new car in well over a decade. Complicating this was that we wanted to register the car in the name of our revocable living trust, which seemed to gum up the works a bit for the financing.

To be honest, we were worn down after about 2 1/2 hours and despite my better judgment, I started signing documents without my usual eagle eye review. When I got home, I started reviewing the documents and realized that I had agreed to some additional warranties that I didn't want and that the financing rate I thought I was getting was not there... I had agreed to a six year financing term when I wanted five year. Oh Great Scott! Now what?

I called the dealership, reached the finance fellow and we met four days after taking possession of the car - and resolved *everything* to my complete satisfaction. He could not have been more accommodating to my requests.

What would have earned AutoNation my highest rating?

Well, it would have been helpful to explain to us what the sales process was going to be. Not everyone purchases a new car every year and we made it clear that we hadn't gone through this in nearly fourteen years. Sort of a simple explanation of "Here's how we will process this sale" step-by-step would have been nice. We were presented numbers that sounded like we were done before we even met the finance guy. And then, the extended warranty information was presented very quickly and, again, we were worn down and didn't push for explanations that could have been more clearly presented to us. Not totally the fault of AutoNation - actually more on us... but they could have presented things more clearly.

But we walked away with a very nice deal on a new car and are totally satisfied that we achieved the correct financing terms with a very honest and reputable car dealership. I wouldn't hesitate to recommend AutoNation Roseville to a friend or neighbor. long, but the people are friendly and actually listen. What a concept: listening to customers!< /review>

They advised me it was a really good price since the service was on sale and it was the last day of the sale, but I told them I wanted to shop for a better price somewhere else. They re-iterated it was a really good price and since my car was already with them they could quickly do the service and have the car back to me within the hour. My experience with AutoNation Honda Roseville was different from any other I've had with a car dealership. I mean this in the most positive way possible.

On May 1st, my beloved 2017 Civic Hatchback Sport was ruled as a total loss after an accident. Being that I live in Elk Grove, I decided to check out the local Elk Grove Honda dealership on May 10th to find a replacement... That was a mistake to say the least. Don't go there if you have any expectation of customer service, no matter how low that may be. I'm not joking when I say that Elk Grove Honda had me test drive a car coated in dust with a giant bird dropping on the door.

After my foul experience with Elk Grove Honda, I gathered quotes from multiple dealerships near the Sacramento area. AutoNation Honda Roseville was super responsive from the get go, Gabe provided a quote through email and followed up with a phone call for more details to help me find the car I really wanted.

After determining that AutoNation Honda Roseville had the lowest quote of the bunch, I called to schedule an appointment. Coleman scheduled to meet with me that same day and we test drove a new 2019 Civic Hatchback Sport. Coleman was super friendly, and really knowledgeable about the car and the new Honda Sensing features that are in the some of the 2019 models. His genuine interest in Honda was apparent, he has one himself!

The whole process was quick. I came in at around 5 and left before sundown. Most importantly, I left in a freshly detailed 2019 Civic Hatchback Sport and my life was no longer disrupted from not having a vehicle.  All my thanks go to the folks at AutoNation Honda Roseville, you're all fantastic!

I absolutely recommend going to this dealership if you're in the market for a car.<//review>

< Review>
Parts buyers beware!

TL/DR: Here are some examples of the prices I used to get. LIST price is the ridiculously inflated price, ACTUAL is the online price I paid when this dealership would price match VS 2019 where they want to scam everyone like every other stereotypical sleazy dealership.

Ignition Switch (small harness with some wires and plastic connector) - LIST: $182.88, ACTUAL: $71.44 = SAVED: $111.44

Oil Pan - LIST: $195, ACTUAL: $77.12 = SAVED: $117.88

Both Headlights - LIST: $460.40, ACTUAL: $302 = SAVED: $158.40

Windshield Wiper Blade - LIST: $26, ACTUAL: $14.11 = SAVED: $11.89

That's the tip of the iceberg based just off receipts I could easily find.

A few years ago there was a great guy in the parts department at AutoNation Honda, I'll call him "P". I asked if he could price match reputable online Honda parts dealers, and his response stuck with me for years.

He was enthused at the idea, and mentioned how he liked the idea of keeping the money in the local Roseville/Sacramento economy instead of going off to various online based-companies, which is becoming the norm these days.

He had the right mindset, and I was able to come in frequently and blow tons of money on parts I didn't really need. He added a fair dollar amount to each of my orders to simulate what would have been a shipping cost if I had bought online.

Recently something has changed at Honda. I don't see "P" around anymore, and everyone at Parts rudely shuts down the concept of being competitive with their prices. I guess my money is going elsewhere.

Look at the latest uploaded photos for some of the (fair) prices I was getting for car parts in 2017-2018 vs what AutoNation Honda wants now. If you have the ability to do things yourself, I recommend doing as much of your own car work as possible. Buy your parts online (reputable Honda sites). There are great Youtube resources available for simple and more advanced repairs.

Zero stars for 2019 Roseville Honda. Shame on you guys. An ignition harness does not cost $180 and you know it.< /Review>

< Review>
So helpful when you want to give them your money, but a NIGHTMARE when you're wanting a refund or decent customer service... In July 2017 I purchased a brand new Vehicle from this dealership. It was fast, easy, and great. I purchased an additional Honda Care Maintenance package at the same time to help maintain my vehicle. Since this time My family and I have moved several states away, and it is a significant inconvenience (Over an hour) to drive to the nearest dealership for vehicle maintenance. I decided to cancel my package for a refund since it was a service I would no longer be using. This is where it goes down hill.... On may 11th I called the dealership and spoke with a man named Eddie who got all my information and said he would email me all the paperwork to fill out and email back to begin the process. I waited and never received an email, so I called the next day to follow up and got a voicemail where I again left my information and informed him I hadn't received any emails. No call back. I called the following Monday and spoke with another Gentleman who said he would pass on my message to Eddie and apparently never did. This began a 3 month process of phone calls, voice mails, and leaving messages with other employees who I'm assuming never passed on my information. No answers, no returned calls, no refund. (Mind you these 3 months are all costing me a portion of my refund.)In early August I returned to Sacramento for a family emergency, and I took an afternoon to drive in and get the situation handled, or so I thought... I went in to the dealership and spoke with a man Named Kerry. I explained the situation and my frustrations and he was very apologetic and helped me to fill out all the paperwork to get sent in. He said the only problem that may arise was since the vehicle was not present they had no way to verify mileage, so he may contact me in a day or two if it posed a problem and I could send a photo of my odometer. I left pleased with my experience, but this was no where near the end... I never received any phone calls, so once I returned home I called and left a voicemail asking him to contact me so I knew if they needed the photo or not. Yet again, beginning a nearly 8 week process of phone calls, voice mails and messages. No contact, no call back, no refund. At 5 months in I was mad, annoyed and just felt completely disrespected. On Sept 27th I sent Kerry an email, reminding him who I was, what was happening and how irritated I was with the entire process. Later that morning I received a short email informing me he would look into it. After a few hours he called informing me they (the people who handle the refunds) were confused on the dates of the paperwork. (Kerry was great and put down the date of May 11th which I appreciated very much, on the refund because that was when I had begun the entire process, even though it was on August 6th that he formally put in the paperwork.) He said he had discussed it with them, and he would contact me as soon as he knew something, (which may take up to a week), but he was very apologetic. Well that week came and went, along with 4 more. I have followed up with phone calls and 2 more emails to which I have received no responses. I am now 1 week shy of a 6 MONTHS into a process which was supposed to take 4 to 6 weeks. I have been in constant contact with my lienholder who have received no paperwork, no refunds, nothing. I have literally received 1 call and 1 email during this entire miserable 6 month process, and neither one apparently did anything. I'm beyond frustrated, I am appalled with the entire process and how helpless and disregarded I feel. They jump thru hoops to sell you a car, but after that apparently you're on your own. If I could give 0 stars, I would. This whole experience has been exhausting, miserable, and beyond frustrating.

UPDATE:: After posting this and more emails and paperwork, I recieved my refund on Nov 29th. Still upset it took me having to post a negative review and be the 'bad guy' to get what was rightfully mine to begin with.</Review>

<rate>2<//rate><Review>This poor review is specific to our experience with internet and Clarity salesperson Kristy L. at Honda AutoNation. She represented herself as an expert in the sales of Clarity vehicles, touting that she is the only one leasing FCVs, yet she is either unaware of or failing to inform customers of the hydrogen fuel shortage. In some parts of California, hydrogen fuel car owners have not been able to drive their cars at all (some for 3-4 months) due to lack of fuel and it will be weeks to months before the infrastructure can catch up.  We would NOT have gotten a hydrogen dependent car had we known all this and I feel Honda should make customers aware of the difficulties in obtaining hydrogen so they can make an informed decision about whether or not this car will work for them. Making this situation further frustrating is we originally went to get the plug-in Clarity, Kristy sold us on the hydrogen one saying it was a better deal since it came with free fuel (by the way the fuel is NOT free, it comes as the cost of your time and inconvenience).

We saw another one on the lot that came so close to hitting the mark - it had everything I wanted, but didn't have AWD. They worked with us until we found the exact combination of features at a price that we could afford. We worked with Nick and he was a total sweetheart. We hadn't planned on purchasing that day and never in my wildest dreams would I have imagined that we'd purchase a BRAND NEW car, but they made us an offer we couldn't refuse and we feel really good about the decision to purchase with Roseville Honda. Everyone was really warm and I never felt pressured along the way. All around it was a great experience for something that can be potentially so scary and anxiety producing.</Review>

<Pictures>None< /Pictures>< Review>
I recently bought my very first brand new car here, a 2017 Accord Sport Special Edition.  I was contacted by Jason from Internet Sales after I used the TrueCar app.  He offered an amazing price right off the bat, below invoice, below what I was already willing to pay.  This was a special Honda was running along with 0.9% financing.  Jason was very laid back, not pushy at all.  There are two things I did not like about my experience.  It took way too long to get me into the finance/warranty guy's office.  I waited for over 2 hours after deciding to buy the car before I could sign the papers which only took me 15 minutes.  I didn't drive the car on the highway during the test drive because of bad 5pm traffic.  On my way home I felt a vibration at highway speeds like out of balance wheels/tires.  I took the car to my local tire shop and they tested the wheels which were in balance.  The tires were the problem, they had flat spots from the car being strapped down to a train, truck, then sitting in a lot for a few months.  I contacted the Service Dept about this and it did take a few calls, meetings, etc., but within a few days they agreed to make the situation right by installing brand new tires and wheels while I waited on my lunch break.  A new car should be perfect from the start, but I'm glad to know that if there is some sort of an issue, AutoNation Honda will take care of it.  My biggest tip to anyone reading this is to treat staff professionally and ask questions, state facts, do not make things personal or make demands and get into a power match against anyone.  If you treat people nicely they'll be much more willing to help you.</Review>

Adrienne Zweifel</Name>
<Time>1507573354807< /Time><Rating>1< /Rating>< review>
Buying a used car from this dealer was a mistake.

I had initially contacted AutoNation for a car and made an appointment with a sales associate for a test drive. He had also sent me a few more cars that I may be interested in, which was really helpful seeing that my car had just been totaled and I had a limited time to find a replacement. When I showed up, the sales associate I had been speaking with was busy with another customer and I was helped by someone else, which was fine. Then no one could find the car I came to see, or any of the cars on the list for that matter. It may have been sold, or maybe not, nobody knew. What they did know was that the list of additional cars that they sent me wasn't actually ready yet. Not wanting the 45 minute drive to be wasted, I had the associate look up other cars that were actually available so I could test drive something at least.

The associate was able to find the Subaru Forester- It had been on the list  and was actually just released. During the test drive, the brakes squealed a little when stopping and he said they were recently replaced. He says normally that goes away after a while. So I bought the car. I would like to say that my sales associate that worked with me was very good and went out of his way to make sure to show me cars that met my criteria. I do not think he knowingly lied about the brakes.

After driving it for a while, the squealing never went away. I contacted the AutoNation Service Department and brought it back so they could fix it. The service department concluded that there was debris on the pads and cleaned/lubricated the parts for free, which I thought was great! Halfway home the squealing started again, but worse than before. I was told by my normal mechanic it was likely that while the brake pads had been replaced, the rotors probably needed to be turned, which wasn't done (or the new pads were really cheap). Now I will spend money to redo the brakes to have it done correctly if I want the squealing to stop.

At the end of the day, I think the Service Department knew what the right thing to do was, and just opted not to do it.< /review>

<review>Bring your wallet. Purchased my used Honda civic here 4 years ago. After experiencing an unusually rough ride on the way up from Los Angeles I booked an appointment on Christmas eve to use a coupon for a free safety inspection.

I arrived at 8am sharp to a line 8 cars deep waiting to be serviced. The check in attendant was very young and had a casual demeanor but checked me in quickly and was kind.

My service rep met me at the car a few minutes later. I neglected to check his name tag, so instead I will say he was a greying gentleman of sturdy stature with a mustache and light colored eyes. He appeared to be in his mid to late 40s.

I stated I was concerned with my Civic's suspension and he said "Well, let's take it for a ride". We hopped in and he drove us around the automall. He couldn't detect the suspension issue I mentioned - the automall roads are very smooth, so I suggested he try going at a speed of 8mph over a bump - which is the base speed I've noticed an issue. He obliged and still said he found no problem.

We went back to the office and sat down. He said the online coupon I had for a free safety inspection would not apply as a service member would also need to drive the car to test the strut. (There was no text on the coupon that said my type of service was omitted, however it did say it was up to shop discression - he could choose to do whatever he wanted).

The fee for a regular safety check is $160 - I was shocked. The rep said "I'm not going to have my tech check it for free if you're not going to get any work done on the car. I think you're just looking for a needle in a haystack". "I will absolutely get work done on the car if there is anything unsafe! If It is unsafe and I have work done on it, do you credit back the service fee?" He answered, "No.". I thanked him and left immediately.

I will never be back.

TLDR: This is the most absurdly expensive service center I have ever been to with the worst service rep experience I have ever had. DO NOT VISIT.<//review></record></dataset><record>

Starting price is $1200 and he'll lead you to believe that it covers all maintenance for the first 4 or so years. He finally had to talk to his manager to give me the "employee price" of $750 but that was still too much for the minimal amount of maintenance that a new car requires. So he settled at $390. That seemed like a fair price for all maintenance for the first four years of a car (thinking oil, brake fluid, filters, rotations, etc). And it included a tire warranty. Now when you get the contract in the mail a couple of weeks later, it clearly says it covers oil changes.. and ONLY oil changes. Four years worth of oil changes does not equate to $390 so I requested to cancel. He claimed that the cancellation required a wet signature when the form clearly states you could fax or email the document. So drove all the way there to sign it in person. Coincidentally he was on the phone the whole time I was there and unable to meet with me. So I got a copy of my filled out form and went about my business. The form states it takes 3-4 weeks to process and now it's been over two months and nothing. Mike fails to respond to all of my follow-ups regarding it. I do not recommend this dealership what so ever. There are other places that value your business. This isn't one of them.<//Review>

While I did have a disappointment experience during my last service visit at Autonation, John more than made up for that lackluster visit.

In short, if you need service on your Honda, see John Davis.  I have no doubt he will make it right for you.

Previous Visit:

My tale of woe began on Sunday, March 26, 2018, when the warning light on my dash indicated the car was experiencing a problem.  I looked up the issue on the all-knowing internet and found that the issue could only be rectified by the dealer. As I had taken off work for the morning and drove 35 miles to get to the dealership, I was not inclined to go away without having the work completed.

My thanks to Gary Pistochini and John Gullo.  But for their intervention and assistance I would have left the dealership with the problem unresolved and I would have wasted the morning.

<Review>I just bought my new 2016 Honda Civic EX from Autonation Honda and am very happy with it and was surprised at the great customer service I received.  I had been researching new cars, but was waiting on my tax refund before buying.  I had just made a visit to a Hyundai dealership, and the salesperson was very nice and helpful, but when it came to talking with the sales manager, he was the cliche pushy, sleazy salesperson we all want to avoid.  I kept telling him I didn't want to buy right now and wanted to think on it, and he made me an unbelievable deal, but I didn't feel comfortable doing business with him.

I didn't get that pushy or sleazy vibe at Autonation Honda.  I had been there a couple weeks earlier talking to Jordon, who was helpful in showing me the different car models I was looking at, but didn't push me on making a sale.  When I went on the day I bought the car, Peter helped show me the features on the car that would be best for me, and showed me the numbers and I said I would have to think about it, but he wasn't pushy either.  He was very personable.  I wouldn't have considered a lease, but Sonny the sales manager spent a great deal of time explaining leasing vs. buying and wanted to make sure I was comfortable with everything, and he was also very personable. They were also willing to hold my check until I received my tax refund, so I wouldn't have to wait to drive home the only blue Honda Civic EX left on the lot.

<text>We had an unusual situation: While we on vacation, 1,000 miles from home, our 2007 Honda Element developed a problem. The Element was completely packed with stuff, including food and wine. It was about 110 degrees outside. Instead of getting it fixed or trying to make it home with a broken vehicle, we decided to buy a new car -- we had already been looking into replace the Element, so we figured this was the opportunity to do so.

We like Hondas, so we went to the AutoNation Honda in Roseville, CA. As we already knew what we wanted, we picked out the car rather quickly, in less than 10 minutes. We didn't need a test drive. We had the money, so we were prepared to write a check for the vehicle ("pay cash").

It took *four* hours to buy the car. FOUR! Why? Well, part of it was because they insisted on doing a credit check on me and my wife, "for identification purposes." (At least they did not use the Patriot Act excuse on us.)

This bordered on intentional fraud. Why? Because, as we've come to find out, there is no statute or law that requires them to perform a credit check on us ‚Äì we had notified them, up front, that we were paying by check (all they needed to do was verify the funds). They never told us that the credit check was entirely optional ‚Äì they repeatedly pressed us to fill out the forms as a requirement to purchase the vehicle.

It is a common tactic, used by some dealerships, to try to get a customer to finance a vehicle. In many cases, when you finance, the dealership gets a percentage of the interest -- making them more money.

What makes this even worse is that running unnecessary credit checks can actually harm a person‚Äôs credit score.

No means NO! Their finance manager insisted on reading, in excruciating detail, all of the "options" we could purchase. I kept saying no, and he kept talking -- wouldn't stop -- even to the point where he would talk over me. At that point, all we wanted to do is write the check, transfer our stuff from the Element into the new car, and leave.

Let‚Äôs break this down:
The salesman: He was OK. He did his best in a bad situation. We weren‚Äôt happy, we were tired, we were hot and my wife was suffering from the symptoms of low blood sugar. However, he was a participant in the, ‚Äúwe need to run a credit check on you for identification purposes,‚Äù scam. He should know better.

The finance manger: Learn how to treat customers with respect; again, no means NO. If he was the one that caused the sales experience to take four hours because he was the one insisting that a credit check be done, then perhaps he needs to be fired. What an awful representative of the dealership.

The DMV person: This is why they got 2 stars instead of 1. She was entirely helpful, communicative and efficient. She helped us get our car titled in our home state within two weeks after we got home. To her, I give a huge THANK YOU.</text><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< response>

Josh Bowen< /user_name>
< Text>
My girlfriend and I were interested in a 2014 Honda Accord EX-L V6. We had done our research for about 6 months and started shopping around at different dealerships. We talked to Reno, Carson City, and Las Vegas dealerships. The lowest quote we got from those dealerships was not what we were looking for. We decided that we would be willing to go to California if the price was right so we decided to put in for a quote through AutoNation Honda.

The very next day we were contacted by Darby Meyer with a quote for $25,975 (almost $3,000 under invoice). Darby was extremely helpful and accommodating. He answered all of our questions over the next couple weeks and never jumped prices around or tried to change what we wanted. After we shopped around a little more to see if we could get a lower price we decided to make the drive to Roseville.

Once we arrived we were immediately greeted by cheerful staff who got Darby right away. We already had the car picked out through their internet service. We were test driving the car within five minutes. After the test drive we decided we would purchase. Everything was very straight forward with very little confusing salesman mumbo-jumbo. Darby did everything he could to make our experience as quick and painless as possible. It was a very busy day so it took about four hours for us to get out with the keys. However, the four hours wasn't spent with us being bombarded by "packages and extras." Darby was not pushy at all and got our paperwork signed and had us sitting with the finance manager as soon as possible. After about 10 minutes with the finance manager we had the final contract signed and keys in our hand. Darby then went so far as to help us figure out some of the technology in the vehicle (However, we already knew most everything due to our extensive research on the vehicle). We were driving off the lot with smiles on our faces in no time at all.

I would highly recommend AutoNation Honda Roseville to anyone looking for a new Honda. AutoNation is a high volume dealership so they really can get you an extremely low price on the exact vehicle you want. Also, ask for Darby Meyer. He was very helpful and not a pushy salesman type. All in all and A+ experience. Thank you Darby and thank you AutoNation Honda Roseville!

Advice for buying a car: Do NOT be in a hurry to purchase a vehicle. Do your research for months before you plan to buy. After you find the exact car you want, start to hunt for the price you want. Try not to test drive until you are ready to buy and have found a deal you want. Cars are just mechanical objects. There are 1,000s of them just like the one you want all over the country. Do not fall in love until you sign the contract and the car is yours. Be open to traveling for a good deal.< /Text>

<rating>5</rating>< review>
For me, AutoNation Honda Roseville gets a 5 out of 5.

They offered no pressure to sell, when I was ready to purchase, they went out of their way to secure pretty much exactly the vehicle I was looking for.. well, my 2nd choice in color, but still very good considering how hard it was to locate the particular car I wanted with the specifics I also wanted in options, as well.

They were friendly and offered a great price on the car as well as finance options.

HOWEVER... Although I've been a long time fan and Honda driver and overall I believe they offer great quality, style and price, regarding the 2015 Fit I just purchased, I have to say for Honda as a company itself (not the dealership itself), I was a bit disappointed.. would have given them 4 out of 5 (possibly lower since the though of having one pay for the cargo cover at such ridiculously high price is a bit infuriating) because they are making me pay for a cargo cover which in every single new car I've ever purchased, was always included (my 93 Acura Intergra included it, my 2003 Mini Cooper S included it, and my 2004 VW R32 included it).. it shouldn't have to be an option to have a cargo cover in the rear of a hatch back, especially!.. and to ask around $200 ($300 to install a clip on piece?!), that's highway robbery!  Not cool, and I really desire and would have expected a rear cargo cover to be included with the car, especially a hatch back so whatever you stow in the rear is covered and out of sight.

Going back to AutoNation Honda Roseville, I want to reiterate my experience was great and that dealership and it's people gets a 5 out of 5.< /review>

< Review>
I bought a 2014 Honda Accord V6 Touring from Autonation Honda Roseville and the overall experience was great. The internet salesperson, Dominick Daurizio, was extremely knowledgeable and easygoing. He let me leave the dealership after my first test drive without any hassle (the Toyota dealership was the complete opposite... I felt like I was being kidnapped). About 2 weeks later, after I had narrowed it down to the car I liked, I came back ready to buy and Dominick was easy to negotiate with. I also had the luxury of having a friend with me who is a GSM at another dealership, so he made cutting through the haggling hassle/process very easy.

The financing went smoothly as well. I brought in a pre-approval from Golden One, which had me at 2.79% APR for 60 months and their department got a me a deal at 1.9% for 60 months. Quick and easy.

My only hangup at all was when I was going over all the warranties and services they offer. I don t remember the gentlemen s name, but he had just bit of that sleazy salesman feel to him. Don t get me wrong, he was polite and all, but even after my buddy (the GSM who knows the ins and outs) told him to please just give us his best prices up front, he still went into cheesy salesman mode. Only after I declined the extremely high priced 7 year warranty (well over $2,000) did he remember that there was some specials and some Honda cash that he forgot about. After dropping the price a bit, and adding an extra year onto the warranty, I went ahead and purchased it. My friend let me know that the price could have gone lower, but it was already close to 11pm and I was ready to get the show on the road.

Overall, I was very happy with my experience purchasing my Honda Accord V6 Touring from them. The sales department was extremely, friendly, fast and accommodating. I m reading a plethora of 1 star comments on their service department, so I m really hoping that I have a positive experience with them when I go in for oil changes and repairs.</Review>
